On Tue, Oct 7, 2008 at 12:51 PM, Mark Petrovic &lt;mspetrovic@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Good day. I am new to JUnit annotations.
&gt;
&gt; I have a need to execute a set of classic account registration tests:
&gt; register a user by [email, password], verify that that succeeds, then
&gt; immediately follow this with an identical registration with the same
&gt; [email, password], which should fail because the account already
&gt; exists. This is a specific case of a more general scenario where the
&gt; first test develops state the second test needs to know about.
&gt;
&gt; It occurred to me to use a single test class, containing two @Test-
&gt; decorated methods: register() and dupRegister(). The problem with
&gt; this structure is that I found no documentation that indicates that
&gt; the first decorated test method is executed after the second decorated
&gt; test method. I also considered using the Parameter annotation, with
&gt; duplicate [email, password] provided as the parameter list. While
&gt; that could drive the tests, I see no way of indicating in this scheme
&gt; that the first test invocation should succeed, while the second should
&gt; fail.
&gt;
&gt; Would someone be kind enough to sketch a reasonable, &quot;JUnit way&quot; to
&gt; approach this.
